cs.CR, cs.DS, cs.AR, cs.PL, cs.SE

Reasoning: 
1. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - The paper deals with the security of Oblivious RAM (ORAM) and proposes a new definition that incorporates timing/termination channel leakage. This makes it highly likely that the paper belongs to the Cryptography and Security sub-category.
2. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper discusses the practical implementation of ORAM, specifically Path ORAM, and proposes a new definition that relaxes the constraints around stash size and overflow probability. This makes it relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms sub-category.
3. cs.AR (Architecture) - The paper deals with the implementation of ORAM in secure processors, which makes it relevant to the Architecture sub-category.
4. cs.PL (Programming Languages) - The paper discusses the behavior of programs and their impact on the length of ORAM access sequences, which makes it relevant to the Programming Languages sub-category.
5. cs.SE (Software Engineering) - The paper proposes a generic framework for dynamic resource partitioning to mitigate internal side channel leakages, which makes it relevant to the Software Engineering sub-category.
